Return to the very American ideal of labor rights as human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have introduced a bill to establish the organization of unions as a civil right.
“Just as unions die, so do middle-class jobs,” said Ellison, a Minnesota Democrat and deputy chairman of the Progressive Caucus in Congress.
That is why I am proud to present the Employee Empowerment Act together with the civil rights icon John Lewis.
This ground-breaking law gives workers the same legal opportunities to discriminate against unions as it does against other forms of discrimination – and thus stops anti-union forces.
The addition of the National Labour Law Act to provide an opportunity for discriminated workers to organize a union representation, to sue for justice in a civil court – and to receive damages or punitive damages – is a meaningful and necessary initiative.
But it is certainly not a radical initiative – at least not by American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis, and the other sponsors of their bill are proposing is to link back to a very American idea.
Despite the setbacks faced by unions in recent years — in Wisconsin, Michigan, and other states across the country — Americans once encouraged countries around the world to recognize, expand, and uphold labor rights.
There was a time millions of Americans still remember when this country called democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and the right of association in one breath.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas Mac Arthur and his staff encouraged the country to pass a constitution to ensure that the militarized autocracy of Hedki Tojo would be replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that the workers and their unions had a role in creating a new Japan, they used a language that explicitly acknowledged that "the rights of workers to union and joint negotiation and action are guaranteed."
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his staff urged the Germans to write a constitution that would ensure that Adolf Hitler’s fascism would be replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers would have to organize and raise their voices in the new nation, the Germans inserted a clause that explicitly stated: “The right to form associations to secure and improve working and economic conditions is guaranteed to every individual and every profession or trade.
Agreements that restrict or aim to diminish this right are null and void; measures aimed at it are unlawful.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt presided over the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights as adopted by the United Nations in 1948 as a worldwide agreement, Roosevelt and the other writers inserted a guarantee that “everyone has the right to form or join trade unions for the protection of their interests.”
For generations, Americans have accepted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
When this country advised other countries on how to form civil and democratic societies, Americans declared that the right to form a trade union - and that this trade union should then be allowed to participate in collective bargaining as an equal partner with companies and government agencies - must be protected.
After these rights have come under attack in America, it is indeed very wise to re-emphasize the American ideal that the working people must have the right to unite and make their voices heard in a free and open society.
As Martin Luther King Jr. said 50 years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the labor movement did not limit the strength of the nation, but increased it.
By raising the standard of living of millions of people, labor has miraculously created a market for industry and raised the entire nation to unimaginable levels of production.
Those who attack work forget these simple truths, but history preserves them.
History remembers, and so should we.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the extension of the protection of civil rights as protection against discrimination in the creation of workers' representatives - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis are renewing the ideals that have made America great in the past and delivered on the promise of democracy.
Judge temporarily halts law that could force all abortion clinics in Louisiana to close
A U.S. federal judge on Sunday provisionally halted the implementation of a law in Louisiana, which lawyers say is believed to have led to the closure of all five of the state’s abortion clinics.
This measure, which was billed by Louisiana Governor Bobby Jindal in June and is due to come into effect Sept. 1, would force doctors performing abortions to acquire a patient admission right at a hospital within a 30-mile radius of their practice.
However, the judge’s decision means that doctors can continue to legally perform abortions while applying for such a right.
"The plaintiffs may continue to operate in accordance with the law while they seek to obtain these rights," federal judge John deGravelles wrote in his ruling.
A hearing for the judge will be held within one month in order to bring about a more permanent decision for the law.
Abortion advocates welcomed the decision, the latest in a series of rulings against similar measures, saying that doctors would gain more time to gain hospital admission rights.
“Today’s decision means that the women in Louisiana are escaping a devious law that wants to take away their health and rights,” said Nancy Northup, president and chairwoman of the Center for Reproductive Rights, which sued on behalf of three of the state’s five clinics to stop the law.
It was not immediately clear whether the verdict also extended to the doctors from the two clinics who had not joined the lawsuit and had also applied for admission rights.
Louisiana is one of 11 states that have passed similar laws, with courts recently declaring such measures unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key points of a Texas law that would have forced most of the remaining clinics in the state to close were stopped by a federal judge on Friday.
Abortion advocates and the American College of Ostretricians and Gynecologists, as well as the American Medical Association, agree that admission rights require doctors to impose unnecessary restrictions.
Opponents of abortion argue that the measures are aimed at protecting women’s health, although some also welcomed the effects of clinic closures.
Only one doctor who performs abortions in Louisiana has patient-instruction rights, the Center for Reproductive Rights said.
If all other doctors in the state were forced to stop performing abortions, this doctor would stop performing the surgery for fear of his safety, the group said.
In their argument against the ruling, Louisiana state officials said they would not punish doctors for performing abortions while their requests for patient instruction rights were pending.
