For those living in rural and remote regions of the state, the mortality risk during the study was 20 percent higher than for those living in urban areas.
Although the study did not investigate why out-of-town women were more likely to die from ovarian cancer, Dr. Jordan suspects a delayed diagnosis and lack of access to the best treatment centers as possible factors for it.
"This disease is best treated by gynecological oncologists, and these are mostly found in larger cities," she said.
Despite improving telemedicine services to counter the distances, she suggested, as a possible remedy, strengthening the service of flown-in doctors to give specialists the opportunity to care for women closer to their place of residence, as well as treatment programs for people outside their region.
