4 Tips for Better Underwater Photos and Videos
If you would like to take photos or videos underwater, there is a selection of devices.
The cheapest option is a waterproof point-and-shoot like the Nikon Coolpix AW120 or an action cam like the GoPro Hero3+ Silver Edition, both available for about $300.
I took these photos at a family party with multiple cameras, all available at a price below $350.
Regardless of the equipment, there are a few rules for the best results.
Check your equipment twice.
Even if you have a waterproof camera, make sure that the battery compartment and other compartments are tightly closed.
Also, set your camera to the photos or videos you want to capture.
Some cameras and camcorders have scene and recording modes that optimize exposure time for the dampest underwater conditions.
And before you jump into it, check to what depth your equipment is functional.
Some cameras are only approved for up to 5 feet, others up to 50 or 60 feet.
Search our shopping guide and reviews for digital cameras for conventional and waterproof models.
Take multiple shots - because many will not work.
Point-and-shoot cameras have an LCD that allows you to compose pictures, action cams usually don’t.
Even if you have an LCD, it is difficult to view this underwater, and the right image setting is a matter of luck.
So take a lot of shots.
If your camera has a series mode that allows you to take a series of shots with slightly changed exposure settings, use it.
Stay close to the surface.
The light gets dramatically worse the further you move away from the surface.
If possible, stay close to the surface when shooting in a pool, lake, or ocean.
This also allows you to add more color to your photos; the deeper you go, the less color you will see.
Get close to the objects.
This is also good advice on land, but it is all the more important underwater because of the poor lighting conditions.
It’s especially important when you’re working with an action cam: These devices often have a fixed wide-angle lens, which means you’ll need to get closer to your objects if you want them to fill in the entire frame.
