When one remembers such things, one becomes powerfully aware of why women of color don’t trust white women.
We didn't do our job well.
We have never helped black women protect their husbands and sons.
Even after women were given the right to vote in 1920, it took another decade for white women to organize against lynching in the Association of Southern Woman for the Prevention of Lynching.
The group emerged nearly 40 years after the original request for help from black women, Mitchell says.
For Mitchell, the tide of white feminist responses to Ferguson’s issues—police behavior, racial discrimination—is a mirror of the time when white feminists “catch” the issues that black women have been grappling with for generations.
“Wouldn’t it be great if the activists who have such traditional feminist platforms took the right to raise a child as seriously as they do the right to control conception?” asked Mitchell.
Second-generation feminists who built their careers on the struggle for reproductive rights and access to contraceptives are now trying to understand what that means.
The well-known white feminist activist Gloria Steinem went on Facebook two weeks after the shooting of Michael Brown and published a pointed article by Rebecca Carroll, columnist of the Guardian, in which she demands more protests from white Americans on the subject of racism.
“I hope that women who have a different but parallel reason to understand a danger inherent in the body — and opinions on race that are markedly different in public polls — will lead the changes,” Steinem wrote.
Although Steinem stands for a rather intersectional feminism in which racial as well as gender issues are addressed, some of her comments on the racial issue in America are baffled.
Christina Sommers, a researcher at the American Enterprise Institute and author of “Who Stole Feminism?” told She The People that young men in the United States, especially young men of color, are “far more vulnerable than their sisters,” but Steinem’s comments on Ferguson are in contrast to her previous criticism.
There are now hundreds of special programs for girls and young women, but almost nothing for boys.
But when the White House recently launched a small program, My Brother’s Keeper, to help vulnerable young black and Hispanic men, there were angry reactions from many feminists, including Gloria Steinem.
The relationship between the police and the black community is not the only problem that is thrusting itself into the forefront of mainstream feminism.
After the U.S. Border Police picked up nearly 63,000 unaccompanied minors at the country’s southwestern border this year, the issue of immigration reform is once again coming to the surface – this time as a women’s issue.
Andrea Mercado, co-chair of We Belong Together, an organization that mobilizes women for immigration reform, said that in order to reimagine the issue as an essential women’s issue, she only had to publish the stories of immigrant women.
