Ebola: Epidemic Affects West Africa's Economy
The Ebola epidemic in West Africa is also a serious blow to the economy.
Markets are orphaned – and international companies are at a distance.
The devastating Ebola epidemic is hitting West Africa’s economy hard.
The harvest rots in the fields, the mines are abandoned and the markets are orphaned - the virus has hit the region hard.
Some international companies are also moving away.
“The Ebola epidemic is not only a medical crisis, but also an economic one,” said African Development Bank chief Donald Kaberuka.
Liberia is the hardest hit
“It’s a total disaster, we’re losing a lot of money,” says Alhaji Bamogo, who sells clothes at the second-largest market in Liberia’s capital, Monrovia.
The only people on the market are those who want to buy food or something to disinfect against Ebola.
Liberia has been hit hardest by the virus, and more than 600 people have died.
Recently, health authorities said the disease had penetrated into every corner of the country.
The virus has also spread to Guinea, Sierra Leone and Nigeria.
In total, more than 1,500 people died, and thousands more were infected.
Foreign companies withdraw employees
Companies are suspending their operations everywhere in resource-rich countries.
Foreign companies such as the steel group Arcelor Mittal are withdrawing their employees, and several international airlines are no longer flying to the affected regions.
Local traders and farmers are also reacting: only a few merchants are still leaving their home towns to get supplies.
In some areas in Sierra Leone and Liberia, which are under quarantine, the cocoa and coffee beans that are important for export rot in the fields, among other things.
The farmers do not dare to leave their homes for the harvest.
Food is scarce
“People will travel less and less,” says Philippe De Vreyer, a Parisian expert on West Africa’s economy.
For example, the man who usually goes to the market and sells his vegetables prefers to stay at home.
The population is therefore directly and urgently affected by the consequences of the epidemic: food is becoming scarce.
In the markets, the supply of staple foods such as rice is dwindling.
At the same time, the region, which is heavily dependent on international companies, threatens to damage its image – with far-reaching consequences.
The biggest danger is that international companies generally avoid the area for a long time, says Philippe Hugon of the French think tank Iris.
It is important to know how far and how long the virus will spread.
"Investors may have the impression that it is dangerous to live in Guinea, Sierra Leone and Liberia and thus to invest," Hugon said.
The disease also affects the strained state budgets of the states
The disease also puts a strain on the already strained state budgets of the affected states.
The rating agency Moody's fears that their budgets will be severely strained by the high expenditure on the health system and in addition by the deteriorating economy.
The African Development Bank has already promised to help the health systems of the affected countries with 60 million dollars (45 million euros).
The effects are already noticeable in Nigeria, where only a few cases of Ebola have been diagnosed so far.
Although the oil-rich region in the southern Niger Delta has not been affected so far.
But elsewhere, many people are already staying at home for fear of being infected.
Reservations in hotels are also falling significantly.
