Genetic disorders often misdiagnosed
One Briton says she thought she would die as a result of a misdiagnosis over many years.
Karin Rodgers lived almost her entire youth believing that she had only a few years left to live after being diagnosed with another disease.
She actually suffered from Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease (CMT) — a group of inherited disorders that damage the nerves outside the brain and spinal cord.
Charity CMT UK reported that misdiagnosis is a common problem in people with CMT because so little is known about this disease.
Around 23,000 people in the UK are thought to suffer from CMT, which can lead to motor disorders such as muscle weakness, an unsafe gait and curved toes.
Sufferers also suffer from numbness or pain. The disease is incurable and progressive, which means that the symptoms get worse over time.
When Rodgers was 13, she believed she was suffering from Friedreich ataxia (FA), a disease with very poor survival.
Rodgers thought she would be in a wheelchair before she turned 18, and die before her 30th birthday.
The mother of two children, who is 51 years old today, said, "As a child, I knew I couldn't do the same as the others.
I fell down constantly and everything took longer with me.
I could never skate or skateboard with the other kids and was often teased at school because of my way of walking and running.
Rodgers said that at the age of 13, after several surgeries to relieve her Achilles tendons and stretch her feet, she saw her medical records when her doctor left the room and read that she was suffering from FA.
"I felt guilty because I had been curious, so I didn't tell anyone this, but I went home, looked for the disease in the library and wrote to the FA society," she said.
When I received an answer, I was shocked and panicked terribly.
I thought I would be in a wheelchair at 18 and die at 25, and slowly lose all my skills in between.
I did it all by myself and planned my own funeral.
She said when she turned 17, she realized that her abilities had not diminished as much as she had imagined and asked her doctor.
He just got up and hugged me and said, "My dear, I don't think you have that, or you'd be in a wheelchair by now."
I think you have something far less life-threatening.
After several genetic tests, she was diagnosed with CMT.
“When he explained to me what CMT was, I felt like I was a winner,” she said.
Charity CMT UK has launched a CMT Awareness Month to raise awareness of this disease.
