Companies in the District, Maryland, and Virginia collectively paid over $10 billion in state and local property taxes last year, compared to $9.6 billion in 2012 — an increase of 4.2 percent over the course of a year.
But the apparent recovery in property values in Maryland is not as effective at increasing state and local tax revenues, as property taxes here amount to just over a fifth of corporate tax returns.
Companies in Virginia and D.C. pay nearly half of their state and local taxes in the form of property taxes.
“In Maryland, much of the real estate, particularly in the tax area around D.C., is either owned by the government or non-profit organizations that don’t pay real estate taxes,” said Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the Center on State Taxation.
Maryland is therefore forced to rely much more on income taxes, for example, in order to be able to provide the same services that other states offer.
The recent recovery in corporate tax revenues cannot be attributed solely to the recovery in the real estate market
Business earnings also appear to be recovering, according to the data.
Companies in the region reported income taxes at state organizations of $2.3 billion compared to $2.1 billion in 2012.
Maryland took in $1 billion in corporate income taxes, the region’s highest amount.
While the trend is in the same direction, the local tax burden for businesses does not rise evenly in all three places.
The rate of increase in the district was 4.3 percent to the national average, while the increase in Maryland was significantly higher, 4.9 percent.
Only Virginia reported a below-average tax revenue of 4.1 percent.
Virginia has the lowest corporate income taxes in all three areas, at 6% (there are fixed corporate tax rates in all three).
