We showed a powerful tribe in our puzzle task of the summer series "Mein Stück vom Rhöner Glück" last Friday.
Several of these tree giants still exist in the district, the specimen shown is the "Gei<0xC3><0x9F>ruheiche" above Unterwei<0xC3><0x9F>enbrunn.
A bumpy footpath leads up to the approximately 600-year-old oak tree.
It passes by pools, basalt stone piles and basalt stone seas.
A little bit below the quarry from Bauersberg, one kilometer north of the road to Weisbach, there it stands.
Vital looks the natural monument, it protrudes beyond the other trees in the area and reminds with a circumference of more than eight meters of an American sequoia tree.
A small Buddha on a tree stump indicates that it is a spiritual or mystical place.
But despite intensive research, there were only indications of the origin of the name.
Dr. Wolfgang Schneider consulted the Bischofsheimer Archive and asked older people from Unterwei<0xC3><0x9F>enbrunn to find out what their relationship is with the Gei<0xC3><0x9F>ruheiche.
The result of his research remained the rather sober explanation for the name.
Until about 80 years ago, the goatherds were said to have driven their animals from Unterwei<0xC3><0x9F>enbrunn to the laboriously cleared and stone-free meadows.
At the foot of the tree are said to have rested the animal guardians exhausted from the ascent.
In the meantime, the area has regained its importance, because goat herds are actually grazing on the meadows again.
The area has also been declared the core zone of the biosphere reserve, Schneider further found out.
However, you should be careful when entering the stone accumulations, because the basalt, warmed up by the sun, is also a popular place for cross otters.
A hiking trail leads from Unterwei<0xC3><0x9F>enbrunn to the tree, but which is somewhat hidden.
Further trails are signposted, climb the direction Hochrhön and invite you to an extended hike.
Where is the water castle?
However, a water castle, which is searched for in our next task, is rather rare to find in height.
The reflection in the ditch already gives a good impression of the building, but we have some historic buildings in the district that could fit the building’s contours.
