After weeks of tug-of-war, Italy’s Prime Minister and Acting EU President, Matteo Renzi, has won the nomination of his Foreign Minister Federica Mogherini as head of EU foreign policy against strong conservative opposition at last week’s EU special summit, she will succeed British Catherine Ashton.
Renzi, as the pro-government daily La Repubblica points out, considers the appointment of his favourite Mogherini, also in the government team, to strengthen the position of the Social Democrats and his own in the EU.
He also expects a boost for his “reform package” in Italy.
Last but not least, Renzi hopes that this will also calm down the left-wing party base, which is always rebelling against him, because Mogherini is assigned to it - albeit rather in a moderate way.
Against the conservative representatives with the President of the Commission Jean-Claude Juncker and the nominated Polish President Donald Tusk, the prevailing opinion in Rome, thus established a political balance.
The EU’s chief diplomat will also be the deputy to Commission President Juncker.
The European Parliament’s pending approval is considered safe.
Otherwise, President Giorgio Napolitano would hardly have called the nomination of the 41-year-old politician of the ruling Democratic Party (PD) an “important recognition” of Italy’s role in the EU.
La Repubblica is spreading optimism that Mogherini, who has been tried and tested in leading party offices for almost two decades and known for her ambition, will be able to cope with the "enormous challenges".
Born in Rome, she is married and has two daughters.
She began her party career in 1996 in the youth organization of the then Democratici di Sinistra (Left-Democrats), which merged with the Catholic Centre Party Margherita in 2008 to form today's Social Democratic PD.
In 1999, Mogherini became vice president of the European Community Organisation of Socialist Youth for three years.
With the election in 2001 to the party council of the Left Democrats, she entered the high party politics, worked in the department of foreign policy, of which she soon became head.
It occupied traditional focuses of Italian foreign policy such as the Middle East, became known through studies of NATO deployment in Afghanistan, in which Italy is involved with a contingent of troops, maintained contacts with the Social Democrats in Europe and with the Democrats in the USA.
Since 2008, she has been a member of the Chamber of Deputies, where she is an expert in defence and European and international affairs.
When Renzi became prime minister in February 2014, he appointed Mogherini as his foreign minister.
If the PD today again has a better relationship with the strong peace movement in the country, which contributed to the party’s over 40 percent vote in the EU elections in May, then as noted in PD circles, Federica Mogherini has a share in it.
The allegations in Brussels that the new EU foreign commissioner has too little diplomatic experience, i.e. that there is a lack of substance, are countered in the PD.
In Brussels, especially by Poland and the Baltic members, Mogherini’s mistrustfully realistic accents on the crisis in Ukraine are being pursued and defamed as a “Russia-friendly course”.
It supports the South Stream pipeline operated by the Russian company Gasprom, through which Russian natural gas is to be transported directly to southern Europe, bypassing Ukraine, which also serves to secure Italy’s energy.
After Renzi took office as EU President in July, Mogherini travelled to Moscow for her first state visit.
Photos she showed with Putin at the shake-hands were taken in Brussels with outrage, as well as inviting the Kremlin chief to a Milan economic summit in October.
