Putin calls on Kiev to start 'state talks' with eastern Ukraine
Russian President Vladimir Putin demanded on Sunday, according to Russian media reports, that the Ukrainian government stop fighting the separatists in the east of the country and immediately start negotiations on the "statehood" of the renegade region.
His spokesman, Dimitri Peskov, later clarified that Putin did not mean that the separatist-controlled territory of eastern Ukraine would become part of Russia, but that his status vis-<0xC3><0xA0>-vis Ukraine would have to be redefined in order to give the Russian-speaking region the power to represent its rights and interests.
Putin’s call to the Kiev government to negotiate on an equal footing with the pro-Russian insurgents, however, fits in with the strategy he has apparently pursued since the start of the riots five months ago: helping the separatists capture territories and putting pressure on the Ukrainian government to allow the newly proclaimed Novorossiya region to become de facto independent for an alliance with Russia rather than with the West.
In an interview with Channel One, Putin condemned the Ukrainian military campaign to retake separatist-held areas in the eastern regions of Donetsk and Luhansk captured in March and April after Moscow annexed the Ukrainian peninsula of Crimea on March 18.
The Kremlin and the separatists have recently referred to the occupied territory as "Novorossia" or "New Russia", a term reminiscent of the pre-revolutionary heyday of the Russian Empire.
Putin pointed out that all those who, in the course of Ukrainian politicians’ campaigns for the elections on Oct. 26, and while government groups are attacking civilian communities in separatist-held areas, hope for early peace talks are “trapped in their illusions,” Itar-Tass reported.
"We must immediately begin detailed discussions, not only on technical issues, but also on the political organization of society and the state status of Southeast Ukraine, in order to safeguard the interests of the people living there," he said.
Peskov said Putin’s reference to statehood must be seen in the context of the greater autonomy that has been under discussion for months by the Kiev leadership to dispel fears in Russian-speaking areas that their cultural and linguistic rights are at risk.
Only the Ukrainian government can grant the eastern territories the necessary autonomy, Peskov said.
Peskov said this is not about negotiations between Ukraine and Russia, "because it is not about a conflict between Russia and Ukraine, but about an internal conflict in Ukraine."
The Kremlin spokesman’s clarification to correct the “misinterpretation” of Putin’s remarks underscored Russia’s leadership in dealing with the separatist rebellion in the East, as opposed to the direct annexation of Crimea, where the majority of the 2 million residents are ethnic Russians.
Moscow would have far greater difficulty in annexing the Donetsk and Luhansk regions in eastern Ukraine, as most of the 6.5 million residents are not Russians and polls from the pre-conflict period showed a broad majority for remaining in Ukraine.
The autonomy addressed by Russian diplomats on international forums would give regional governments in Ukraine authority to negotiate their own trade agreements and foreign relations, thus giving the Kremlin de facto control over an area that connects Russian territory with Crimea.
The Black Sea peninsula, which was annexed five months ago, is the home port for the majority of the Russian Navy, as well as an important commercial port and historic coastal region.
The regions between the Rostov region in Russia and Crimea are also rich in mines, factories and foundries that produce important components for the Russian military.
Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko, in his inaugural speech on 7 June, suggested that Ukrainian legislation, after new elections, should consider additions to the Constitution, which would give the respective territories greater control over their finances and the status of languages.
But his idea of autonomy seems to be in sharp contrast to those of the Kremlin and the separatist rebels, whose arming and incitement Moscow is accused of.
Putin’s last call for Kiev to negotiate with the separatist leaders on an equal footing followed a further incursion by the rebels last week after Russian troops and tanks invaded eastern Ukraine over the previously peaceful region along the Sea of Azov.
The Russian-backed separatists took control of Novoazovsk, which Ukrainian security officials fear is the first step in a campaign to take over the strategic coastal region as far as Crimea.
For this reason, massive civil and military preparations have begun to fortify Mariupol, a steel industrial port with 500,000 inhabitants located between Novoasovsk and the narrow access to the Crimean Peninsula.
Speaking at a meeting of EU leaders in Brussels on Saturday, Poroshenko urgently called for action to prevent another Russian aggression against Ukraine, a former Soviet republic that has been independent for 23 years.
"We are on the verge of a point where there is no turning back," Poroshenko warned.
Thousands of foreign troops and hundreds of foreign tanks are now on the territory of Ukraine.
The EU summit decided on no concrete actions, the leadership demanded the draft of further sanctions against Russia, which should come into force in the event of an unspecified escalation of the Ukraine crisis.
Ukrainian soldiers had to withdraw from their positions in Ilovaysk after two Russian tank columns and 1,000 soldiers invaded the Donetsk region last week to support the besieged separatists, said Colonel Andriy Lysenko, spokesman for the Ukrainian National Security and Defense Council reports Saturday in Kiev.
The first probably 63 Ukrainian soldiers trapped by the Russian invasion of Ilovaisk were exchanged on Sunday for 10 Russian paratroopers who had been captured on Ukrainian territory a week ago, Lysenko said on Sunday.
